In `ctrodb`, adapters handle persistence and storage backends [5]. The library ships with two built-in adapters, both supporting transactional rollbacks if an error is thrown during execution [1, 2].

### Built-in Adapters Comparison

| Adapter | Environment | Persistence | Best Used For |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `MemoryAdapter` | Node.js, Browser | Not persisted [1] | Testing, temporary state, server-side environments [7] |
| `IndexedDBAdapter` | Browser only [1] | Persisted [1] | Production client-side web applications |

---

### Complete Example: Initializing Adapters and Transactions

Below is a complete example showing how to initialize both adapters and execute a transaction [2, 4].

```javascript
import { Database, MemoryAdapter, IndexedDBAdapter, Schema } from 'ctrodb';

// 1. Define a schema for demonstration
const userSchema = new Schema({
  name: { type: String, required: true }
});

async function main() {
  // Initialize Database with MemoryAdapter
  const memDb = new Database({
    adapter: new MemoryAdapter(),
    schemas: { users: userSchema }
  });
  await memDb.connect();

  // Initialize Database with IndexedDBAdapter (Browser only)
  const idbDb = new Database({
    adapter: new IndexedDBAdapter({ dbName: 'my-local-db' }),
    schemas: { users: userSchema }
  });
  await idbDb.connect();

  // Execute a transaction (all changes rollback if callback throws) [2]
  try {
    await idbDb.adapter.transaction(async () => {
      const users = idbDb.collection('users');
      await users.create({ name: 'Alice' });
      await users.create({ name: 'Bob' });

      // This error triggers a rollback of 'Alice' and 'Bob' insertions
      throw new Error('Force rollback');
    });
  } catch (error) {
    console.log('Transaction failed and changes rolled back:', error.message);
  }
}

main();
```

---

### Adapter Interface Configuration

| Property / Method | Type | Description |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `transaction(fn)` | `Promise<void>` | Executes a batch of operations. Rolls back on error [2]. |
| `dbName` (IndexedDB) | `string` | The database name inside the browser's IndexedDB engine. |

